  "final_text": "The probe selection worked, but gdb timed out connecting to the N6 \u2014 this matches a known flakiness with N6 connections (DBG-012). Trying once more before reporting back:\nThe session can't come up \u2014 here's where it stands:\n\n**What happened:**\n1. First attempt failed with `Multiple debuggers detected` \u2014 two probes on the bench (NUCLEO-L476RG + **STM32N6570-DK**).\n2. Pinned the N6 probe (`SN 003400303235511638363730`) and retried with `--n6-dev-mode` (BOOT confirmation answered yes per your message).\n3. gdbserver now starts fine, but **gdb's `target-select extended-remote localhost:61234` times out after 10s** (`gdb_marker: command-timeout`) \u2014 twice in a row.\n\n**Why this is likely:** this is the known DBG-012 behavior \u2014 gdb connecting to a running N6 hangs, and the N6 connection is generally flaky. The substrate's hint is \"raise the per-call timeout or check target liveness.\"\n\nPer HIL mode I'm stopping here rather than retrying further. The usual fix:\n\n- **Power-cycle the N6570-DK** (unplug/replug USB) now that BOOT is in dev position \u2014 the dev-mode boot setting only takes effect on a fresh boot, and a stale-booted target is the classic cause of this exact hang.\n- Then I'll re-run the start.\n\nWant me to retry after you've power-cycled the board?"
}